@Node "CONCEPT" "CONCEPTS & FEATURES"


 CONCEPT
 -------

  Have you ever been on your favorite IRC channel and been afraid to
 leave (to get a snack, answer a phone, spank the dog) in case you miss
 something?

  Now you'll never miss a thing...

  Narrator uses the Amiga's built in speech capabilities to narrate the
 messages people type.

  If nothing else, this script with have you rolling on the floor,
 laughing...


 FEATURES
 --------

 Screening  ('Private Messages' button)
 ~~~~~~~~~
   Narrator can be told to speak ONLY those messages that are sent to
  you via /msg.

 Random Voices  ('Random Voice' button)
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   Narrator can randomize the pitch of the voice.

 Voice Control  ('Pitch', 'Speed' & 'Inflection' gadgets)
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   Narrator allows user control of the voice style via simple arguments.

 Flooder Muting  ('Speak Everything' button)
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
  Narrator can speak everything people type, or can speak only the first
 line in a row, eating the second, third, ect. lines.  This is useful for
 busy channels and DCC notifications.

 Smiley/Acronym Interpretation  ('Smileys & Acronyms' button)
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   Narrator can translate @{"smileys & acronyms" Link "SMILEY"} into phrases.
  If someone types 'BRB', Narrator will speak "BE RIGHT BACK"
  If someone types ':)', Narrator will speak "grins"

 Smiley/Acronym Editor
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   This is currently unavailable in the shareware version.
  You could, however, edit the NarratorConfig manually, but I don't suggest
  this method.

 Applications Editor
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   This is currently unavailable in the shareware version.


@EndNode
@Node "SYSREQ" "REQUIREMENTS"


 REQUIREMENTS
 ------------

  Narrator requires 'AmIRC' (tested with V1.41) and 'SPEAK:' device
 mounted.  'MUIRexx' is also required and should reside in 'SYS:Rexxc/'

 AmiNET:comm/tcp/amirc.lha
 AmiNET:dev/mui/MUIRexx_2_2.lha  (if you use Kuang¿¿,
                                  then you already have this installed)

  If you don't have the SPEAK: stuff it is in v2.04 of Workbench
 (and possibly earlier versions, I'm not sure), but unfortunately
 not in v3.0+.  :/

  A SPEAK: mountlist is included.  It requires this;

  'narrator.device'     installed in  DEVS:
  'speak-handler'       installed in  L:
  'translator.library'  installed in  LIBS:
  'SPEAK'               installed in  DEVS:DOSDRIVERS/
  'SPEAK.info'          installed in  DEVS:DOSDRIVERS/

  I have heard that Narrator can CRASH if you do NOT have SPEAK:
 mounted.  It is NOT enough to just have the SAY program working.

  One way to test SPEAK: is to type the following line in a cli;

 ECHO 'testing' >SPEAK:

  If you hear the word 'testing' spoken, then Narrator WILL work.


@EndNode
@Node "INSTALL" "INSTALLATION"


 INSTALLATION
 ------------

  Installation can be done using any directory utility.

  This is where you need to put the files.  A directory named 'Narrator'
 must be created in AmIRC:

  AmIRC:Narrator/NarratorGUI.rexx
  AmIRC:Narrator/NarratorConfig
  AmIRC:REXX/Narrator.amirx
  HELP:Narrator.guide

   To start Narrator, in AmIRC just type...

 /rx Narrator

  ...or add an alias like this...

 /alias Speak /rx Narrator

  Then all you need to do to start the Narrator is type '/Speak'.


@EndNode
@Node "USAGE" "USAGE"


 USAGE
 -----

  When you start Narrator via '/Speak' or a similar alias, the GUI
 will open.  Set the gadgets to your taste, and when you are satisfied,
 PRESS 'Save'.  This will save the settings and send them to the Narrator.

 NOTE:  The settings will not take effect until someone (other than you)
        types something.  If you don't want to wait for that, just send
        yourself a message via /msg, or just double-click on your name.

  If for some reason you want to temporarily mute Narrator, PRESS 'Shutup!'.
  If you then PRESS 'Speak!', it will start up again.

  PRESSing 'Quit' shuts Narrator off.  (go figure)

  For further help, simply use the bubble-help facility provided by
 MUI.  Make sure this feature is turned on in MUI Settings...

 ...or press the 'HELP' key to load this document.


@endnode
